<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Under laboratory conditions and injection of hyphal bodies into the haemocoel of insects, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. militaris" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="militaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">C. militaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can infect many insect orders (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-012-0825-y" author="Shrestha, B" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Progress" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="599 - 614" refId="B82" refString="Shrestha, B, Zhang, WM, Zhang, YJ, Liu, XZ, 2012. The medicinal fungus Cordyceps militaris: research and development. Mycological Progress 11 (3): 599 - 614, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-012-0825-y" title="The medicinal fungus Cordyceps militaris: research and development." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-012-0825-y" volume="11" year="2012">Shrestha et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
), including pupae of 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Tenebrio" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tenebrio molitor" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="molitor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Tenebrio molitor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Hexapoda" family="Tenebrionidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tenebrionidae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01650457" author="De Bary, A" journalOrPublisher="Botanische Zeitung" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="17 - 21" refId="B14" refString="De Bary, A, 1867. Zur Kenntniss insectentoedtender Pilze. Botanische Zeitung 25: 17 - 21, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01650457" title="Zur Kenntniss insectentoedtender Pilze." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01650457" volume="25" year="1867">De Bary 1867</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1303/aez.2002.85" author="Sato, H" journalOrPublisher="Applied Entomology and Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="85 - 92" refId="B77" refString="Sato, H, Shimazu, M, 2002. Stromata production for Cordyceps militaris (Clavicipitales: Clavicipitaceae) by injection of hyphal bodies to alternative host insects. Applied Entomology and Zoology 37 (1): 85 - 92, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1303/aez.2002.85" title="Stromata production for Cordyceps militaris (Clavicipitales: Clavicipitaceae) by injection of hyphal bodies to alternative host insects." url="https://doi.org/10.1303/aez.2002.85" volume="37" year="2002">Sato and Shimazu 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Therefore, the conclusion that wireworms (e.g. 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Tenebrio" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tenebrio molitor" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="molitor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Tenebrio molitor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) are the natural hosts of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. militaris" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="militaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">C. militaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably untenable and we temporarily reject it.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
